snippet.textDisplay: This composition was a mess from the very beginning. Yes Ai Giri Nandini is NOT Tamil, but purely Sanskrit. Secondly, the title of the song should have been 'Ai Girinandini' not 'Aigiri Nandini'. The latter  does not make any sense and clearly shows that these people have not even tried to understand the first word of the stotram. Third, Arunaji pronounces "nandinute"..which should have been "nandanute" as per most of the Sanskrit texts. And the fusion did not work at all.

snippet.textDisplay:
Sona, I'm a great fan of your songs. I love your "Tere Ishq Nachaya"; I can listen to it over and over again.
Likewise, Ms. Sairam, I adore "Aigiri Nandini". It is so deep and sacred and strengthening; I could listen to it forever.
However, the fusion of these two to my ears was, frankly speaking, a total mess. I'm surprised neither of you thought so (which is presumably why you even let the music directors carry on with this charade). As custodians of our music industry, please be more prudent.

snippet.textDisplay: I am from Chennai. I know the value/power of this classical devotional song. But, after my school days, I stopped listening to devotionals, cos of the repetitiveness.
